### PHP for Loop

The `for` loop is used when you know in advance how many times you want to execute a block of code.

### Syntax

```php
<?php
for (init; condition; increment) {
    // code to execute
}
?>
```

### Example

```php
<?php
for ($i = 0; $i < 5; $i++) {
    echo "Number: $i<br>";
}
?>
```

### Parts of for Loop

| Part | Description | Example |
|------|-------------|---------|
| Init | Execute once at start | `$i = 0` |
| Condition | Checked before each iteration | `$i < 5` |
| Increment | Execute after each iteration | `$i++` |

### Variations

```php
<?php
// Multiple init statements
for ($i = 0, $j = 10; $i < 5; $i++, $j--) {
    echo "$i - $j<br>";
}

// Omitting parts
$i = 0;
for (; $i < 5; $i++) {
    echo "$i<br>";
}
?>
```

> **Key Point:** The `for` loop is ideal for iteration when the number of iterations is known, such as looping through array indices.
